'''''Death Star''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] novel written by [[Michael Reaves]] and [[Steve Perry]]. It was first published in hardcover by [[Del Rey]] on [[October 16]], [[2007]], and a paperback edition was published in [[2008]]. It focuses on an ensemble cast of [[DS-1 Orbital Battle Station/Legends|Death Star]] crew members, and it spans a three-[[Standard year/Legends|year]] period that concludes with the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]].

==Publisher's summary==
''The Death Star's name says it all, with bone-chilling accuracy. It is a virtual world unto itself&mdash;equipped with uncanny power for a singularly brutal purpose: to obliterate entire planets in the blink of an eye. Its annihilation of the planet Alderaan, at the merciless command of Grand Moff Tarkin, lives in infamy. And its own ultimate destruction, at the hands of Luke Skywalker, is the stuff of legend. But what is the whole story, and who are the players, behind the creation of this world-killing satellite of doom?''

''The near extermination of the Jedi Order cleared the way for Palpatine&mdash;power-hungry Senator and Sith Lord&mdash;to seize control of the Republic, declare himself Emperor, and usher in a fearsome, totalitarian regime. But even with the dreaded Darth Vader enforcing Palpatine's sinister will, the threat of rebellion still looms. And the Emperor knows that only abject fear&mdash;and the ability to punish dissent with devastating consequences&mdash;can ensure his unchallenged control of the galaxy. Enter ambitious and ruthless government official Wilhuff Tarkin, architect of the Emperor's terrifying dream come true.''

''From inception to completion, construction of the unprecedented Death Star is awash in the intrigues, hidden agendas, unexpected revelations, and daring gambits of those involved on every level. The brightest minds and boldest egos, the most ambitious and corrupt, the desperate and the devious, all have a stake in the Death Star&mdash;and its potential to control the fate of the galaxy.''

''Soldiers and slaves, loyalists and Rebels, spies and avengers, the innocent and the evil&mdash;all their paths and fates will cross and intertwine as the Death Star moves from its maiden voyage to its final showdown. And a shadowy chapter of ''Star Wars'' history is stunningly illuminated in a thrilling, unforgettable adventure.''

==Plot summary==
During the final phases of construction and activation of the [[DS-1 Orbital Battle Station/Legends|first Death Star]], several low-level crewers bond together in opposition to the [[Battle station/Legends|battle station's]] monstrously destructive mission. Following the obliteration of the [[Planet/Legends|planets]] [[Despayre]] and [[Alderaan/Legends|Alderaan]], this assortment of conscientious personnel from different walks of life arrange escape from the battle station during its approach to the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel]] base on [[Yavin 4/Legends|Yavin 4]]. They flee the Death Star before it is annihilated and seek refuge with the Rebels. Among these [[Desertion/Legends|deserters]] are:

[[Celot Ratua Dil]]: A convicted [[Smuggler/Legends|smuggler]] sentenced to [[Prison/Legends|imprisonment]] on the penal world of Despayre, which also served as a construction site for the Death Star, the crafty Ratua sneaks aboard a [[Transport/Legends|transport]] to escape confinement and manages to carve a survivable niche aboard the Death Star posing as a civilian contractor for two [[Standard year/Legends|years]]. He falls in love with [[Memah Roothes]], [[Bartender/Legends|bartender]] at the onboard [[Cantina/Legends|cantina]], the [[Hard Heart Cantina/Legends|Hard Heart]].

[[Kornell Divini|Kornell “Uli” Divini]]: An [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[Doctor/Legends|surgeon]] conscripted into service after the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], Uli grows weary of wartime duty. While stationed aboard the Death Star, he tends to captive [[Princess/Legends|Princess]] [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia Organa’s]] trauma after her Imperial interrogation and grows to sympathize with her cause. His research into [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force sensitivity]] puts him on the Imperial wanted list just prior to the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]].

Memah Roothes: A bartender formerly based in the [[Southern Underground/Legends|Southern Underground]] of [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]]. When Memah's cantina on Coruscant, the [[Soft Heart Cantina|Soft Heart]], mysteriously burns down, the Empire recruits her to run a similar business aboard the Death Star. She brings with her [[Rodo]], a hulking [[Ragithian Human|Ragithian]] [[Bouncer (occupation)/Legends|bouncer]]. She develops feeling for Ratua despite his shady past.

[[Villian Dance|Villian “Vil” Dance]]: A hotshot [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter/Legends|TIE fighter]] [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] always seeking a challenge, Vil grows to respect the Rebellion and is disturbed by the numerical superiority of the Empire. He falls in love with [[Architect/Legends|architect]] [[Teela Kaarz]]. When the Death Star obliterates Alderaan, it seals his commitment to leaving Imperial service. He pilots the escape [[Shuttle/Legends|shuttle]] away from the battle station, even briefly outflying [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] during the Battle of Yavin.

Teela Kaarz: An architect and [[Politics/Legends|political]] prisoner incarcerated on Despayre, Teela is conscripted to help design and build interior spaces aboard the Death Star. Among the projects that passed her desk was a certain [[Thermal exhaust port/Legends|thermal exhaust port]] that would later prove to be the Death Star's exploitable weakness. Teela falls in love with Vil Dance, TIE fighter pilot.

[[Nova Stihl]]: An [[Guard Sergeant|Imperial guard]] and [[Martial artist/Legends|martial arts instructor]], Nova is troubled by vivid dreams and flashes of [[Force vision/Legends|vision into the future]]. Examined by Dr. Divini, Nova discovers that he is Force-sensitive. During the rush to escape the Death Star, Nova and the bouncer Rodo – a sparring partner – stay behind to hold off pursuing Imperial guards. Rodo and Nova are [[Death/Legends|killed]] in the exploding Death Star.

Aside from this desertion, the final phases of the Death Star's life are marked by other dramas. [[Imperial gunner/Legends|Gunner]] [[Tenn Graneet]] struggles with his role in firing the battle station's devastating [[Laser cannon/Legends|cannon]] against planets, but he nonetheless continues to serve the Empire loyally. Meanwhile, incidents of [[Saboteur/Legends|sabotage]] plague the Death Star's final phases. [[Grand Moff/Legends|Grand Moff]] [[Wilhuff Tarkin/Legends|Tarkin]] instructs his secret lover, [[Admiral/Legends|Admiral]] [[Nataasi Daala|Daala]], to investigate these incidents. She is injured during a Rebel attack and must undergo emergency [[Brain/Legends|brain]] surgery that [[Memory wipe/Legends|wipes her memory]] of these events.

==Development==
Authors [[Michael Reaves]] and [[Steve Perry]] intended to give [[Conan Antonio Motti/Legends|Motti]] the first name "Zi" in ''Death Star'', and the name was approved by [[Lucasfilm]]. However, after [[George Lucas]] jokingly named the character "Conan Antonio" on [[Wikipedia:Late Night with Conan O'Brien|''Late Night with Conan O'Brien'']] in [[2007]], a last-minute editorial change was made.<ref name="Insider">{{InsiderCite|96|Jawa's Corner}}</ref> One occurrence of "Zi" remains in the novel's thirty-eighth chapter.<ref name="Death Star" />

==Continuity==
The ''Death Star'' novel spanned the [[Battle station/Legends|battle station's]] last three [[Standard year/Legends|years]], culminating with its destruction at the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]]. In ''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'', in its reading chronology, the book was placed before the events of ''[[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope]]'', so that the movie could be experienced first. Though the novel incorporated story threads from across the [[Star Wars Legends|Expanded Universe]], including nods to the ''[[Star Wars: The Jedi Academy Trilogy]]'' ([[1994]]-[[1995]]) and the short story ''[[Interlude at Darkknell]]'' ([[1999]]), noticeably absent was the [[DS-1 Orbital Battle Station/Legends|Death Star's]] role as a location in [[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed|''The Force Unleashed'']] ([[2008]]). It was because the game's story line would not be publicly disclosed until its launch a year after the ''Death Star's'' publication.<ref name="ERC" />

